On June 10, 2025, the Committee ordered H.R. 3633, as amend-
ed, to be reported favorably to the House by a recorded vote of 32
yeas and 19 nays, a quorum being present. (Record Vote No. FC–
169).
The Committee considered the following amendments to H.R.
3633:
• Representative French Hill (R–AR) offered an amendment
in the nature of a substitute, which requires the prudential
regulators to develop capital requirements for financial institu-
tions that address netting agreements, clarifies that certain
blockchain developers and service providers that do not cus-
tody or control consumer funds are not classified as money
transmitters, requires rulemaking regarding disclosures re-
lated to the treatment of certain assets held by SEC reg-
istrants in the event of their insolvency and the use of certain
exemptions under securities laws, and makes minor edits and
technical changes. This amendment was adopted by a voice
vote.
• Representative Maxine Waters (D–CA) offered an amend-
ment (No. 6), designated HR3633_T01. This amendment would
prohibit the President, Vice President, Members of Congress,
and certain members of their families from participating or
trading—directly or indirectly—in digital asset projects. This
amendment failed by a recorded vote of 21 yeas and 30 nays,
a quorum being present. (Record Vote No. FC–142).
• Representative Brad Sherman (D–CA) offered an amend-
ment (No. 7), designated SHERMA_047. This amendment
would prevent federal agencies from providing financial assist-
ance to digital asset issuers and exchanges in the event of fail-
ure or bankruptcy through any emergency liquidity facility or
the Exchange Stabilization Fund. This amendment failed by a
recorded vote of 21 yeas and 30 nays, a quorum being present.
(Record Vote No. FC–143).
• Representative Sherman offered an amendment (No. 8),
designated SHERMA_050. This amendment would prohibit the
Federal Government and Federal Reserve banks from pur-
chasing digital assets. This amendment failed by a recorded
vote of 21 yeas and 30 nays, a quorum being present. (Record
Vote No. FC–144).
• Representative Waters offered an amendment (No. 9), des-
ignated HR3633_T27. This amendment would require a person
acting as a broker, dealer, or Alternative Trading System for
blockchain-based securities to register with the SEC and all
the states in which they seek to operate. This amendment
failed by a recorded vote of 21 yeas and 30 nays, a quorum
being present. (Record Vote No. FC–145).
• Representative Waters offered an amendment (No. 10),
designated HR3633_T25. This amendment would establish a
bill of rights for crypto investors that requires digital asset
trading platforms to develop policies and procedures to uphold.
