INCREASED INVESTOR HARM
The CALAMITY Act includes several sections that will increase
and create new harm to investors. A few of these provisions in-
clude:
1. Section 106 creates a provisional registration process that
would allow entities to escape regulation and oversight while
the rules of the bill are written. To make matters worse, the
provisional registration process is silent on whether the SEC
or state regulators may bring enforcement actions against an
entity that has filed a statement of provisional registration, so
harmed investors would have little recourse from these enti-
ties.
2. Section 202 would bring unprecedented risk to investors
through a new exemption at the SEC, labeled the 4(a)(8) ex-
emption. It would allow crypto firms to raise $75 million per
year for four years, if they intend to become a ‘‘mature
blockchain system’’ (which is explained below). This exemption
allows firms to engage in general solicitation of retail inves-
tors, which means that everyday investors could be peddled se-
curities, which would not include audited financials or issuer
obligations to continually disclose material facts about the
project. Non-accredited investors (i.e., retail investors) would
be able to purchase crypto assets up to all of their net worth
or annual income, which is a stark contrast to the Regulation
A (‘‘Reg A’’) exemption, which limits non-accredited investors to
investing up to 10% of their income or net worth.25 Firms tak-
ing advantage of Reg A must provide audited financials,26 a
business description, material risk factors, use of proceeds, and
other disclosures.27 They also are subject to ongoing reporting
requirements28 and SEC approval29 for the offering.30 Most
worryingly, state securities regulators are explicitly barred
from regulating this new exempt offering even though the SEC
rarely brings enforcement actions when harms are small. And
inexplicably, there are no requirements that the funds raised
by a crypto company must go towards developing the crypto
business or its blockchain, as is required of other securities of-
ferings.
3. Section 205 creates a mechanism for ‘‘digital commodity
issuer, digital commodity related person, digital commodity af-
