STATE PREEMPTION
This legislation also takes the state securities regulators off the
frontlines of fighting fraud. The CALAMITY Act is silent on wheth-
er state securities regulators have antifraud, investigation, and ex-
amination authorities, as well as the authority to regulate the bro-
kerage and investment advisory industries.
At best, states would be forced to spend enormous resources liti-
gating and proving in courts that the states still have these au-
thorities to help prevent and fight fraud.43 The CALAMITY Act’s
silence could also result in multiple de facto regulatory gaps that
foster fraud and leave victims without recourse. For example, the
U.S. federal government almost never takes on cases where the
harmed investor’s losses are small. By contrast, state securities
regulators regularly pursue cases under $1 million to help the vic-
tim recover what may amount to their entire lifesavings.
ANTICOMPETITIVE BUSINESS PRACTICES
Anticompetitive business practices restrict competition in the
market and can lead to monopolies or dominant firms that leave
smaller businesses with high barriers to entry. This bill bakes in
the harmful practices by dominant crypto firms, allowing them to
consolidate power within one company, known as vertical integra-
tion. The CALAMITY Act would allow the same entity, and affili-
ates it controls, to comingle the following functions, that are sepa-
rate under today’s securities laws to avoid clear conflicts of inter-
est: running an exchange facility; operating an alternative trading
system; conducting broker-dealer activity; settling and clearing
trades; custodying assets; and offering wallet services. This legisla-
tion also does not include best execution requirements, which re-
quire brokers to carry out customer orders under the most favor-
able conditions to customers.44 Under this bill, exchanges would
also not have to post the National Best Bid or Offer (NBBO), which
is a stock quote available market wide that represents the highest
buy price and the lowest sell price for a security trading on various
exchanges.45 The NBBO was created by the SEC to ensure cus-
tomers get the best available price at the time of a trade, no matter
where they execute their trade.46
Additionally, the biggest traditional finance entities, including
the big banks, will be empowered by the complexities of this bill
because they will be the best equipped to game the loopholes cre-
ated by this bill and ensure all of their activity comes under the
light touch regulation the bill provides. This means less investment
for crypto entrepreneurs. This bill would also codify the dominance
of the largest crypto firms, at the expense of startups in the space.
